entry.title: media: Add secure buffers to VideoDecoderPipeline
entry.content:
Adds handling of secure buffers (when the decoder uses them) to the

VideoDecoderPipeline. This will be used with the ARM V4L2 implementation

of secure playback. The pipeline will request a secure handle from the

decoder (this handle is just an integer specifier, not the actual

resource handle which will be managed by the V4L2Queue). It then

attaches that handle to the DecoderBuffer and performs the Decrypt

operation on it. The secure handle remains with the DecoderBuffer as it

works its way through the rest of the pipeline.



The actual secure buffer (in TrustZone memory) stores the decrypted (or

copied if it's clear) data from the DecoderBuffer for use later in the

secure video decoding process.



This also updates my email address in the OWNERS file to the one I

actually use for reviewing/submitting changes.

entry.title: Explicitly show/hide suggestions for text elements
entry.content:
Currently, TextControlElements show and hide suggestions based on the

value of the suggestion itself. If the suggested value is empty, it

means that there's no suggested value to show and we should hence show

the actual value of the field, otherwise, we should hide the value and

show the suggested value.



While this method worked pretty well until now, it stops working when

the Autofill Undo project comes into perspective. Consider a field that

was initially empty and then autofilled. Undoing the autofill would

revert the field to being empty. When previewing this undo operation,

the field's suggested value should be the empty string.



This CL bases the show/hide behavior of inner editor values of

TextControlElement on the nullness of the string instead of its

emptiness, so that empty suggested values can be shown.

entry.title: [exo] Add ClientTracker class to exo/wayland
entry.content:
Currently the destruction of wl_client may result in callbacks into

chromium code part way through the destruction and freeing of its

associated resources.



This can cause issues if code attempts to query the wl_client's

resources after destruction, which can result in UAF crashes (see

crbug.com/1433187 where iterating over wl_client resources resulted

in crashes).



This CL introduces a ClientTracker class that keeps track of whether

a given wl_client instance has started destruction.



Follow up CLs will integreate this into Exo into a more accessible

location and replace existing code that attempts to do the same

in a more bespoke way.

entry.title: Keep notifications alert helper alive during permission request.
entry.content:
When using the UNUserNotifications API we need to make sure the alerts

helper isn't terminated while we're still waiting for a response to

the permission request, as doing so would abort our only chance of

asking for permission.



This is implemented by adding a new OkayToTerminateService IPC and use

that instead of querying the displayed notifications. The NS

implementation of this IPC just queries for displayed notifications,

while the UN implementation additionally checks for the permission

state.

entry.title: Prevent glanceable scroll while closing the bubble
entry.content:
Fixes a DCHECK when glanceables view gets updated while closing the

bubble widget. DCHECK was happening while trying to update the scroll

view's scroll offset in response to the glanceable child bubble height

changing. The issue was more likely for tasks glanceable, as the client

runs all pending tasks callbacks when the bubble closes, but with

certain timing, it was possible for classroom glanceable too.



In addition to checking whether widget is closing before updating the

scroll view scroll offset, adds hooks to invalidate pending tasks, or

classroom assignment callbacks when the glanceables widget starts

closing. This avoids unnecessary UI updates if tasks/assignment

callbacks get called when the glanceables widget is about to be hidden.

entry.title: Move NativeWidgetMac::SetSize implementation to remote_cocoa.
entry.content:
The current bounds as known to NativeWidgetMac can often be outdated or

incorrect. If SetSize uses the origin as currently cached in the browser

process it is possible to undo a previous window move depending on what

OnWindowGeometryChanged have or have not been received yet. To avoid

such problems, this CL changes NativeWidgetMac::SetSize to just forward

the new size to remote_cocoa, having the logic to actually determine the

new bounds based on that size therw.



Ideally we wouldn't try to replicate any bounds calculations in the

browser process (as this still leaves the locally cached bounds

potentially incorrect for the time in between the SetSize call and

the resulting OnWindowGeometryChanged being called by remote cocoa),

but views code in general unfortunately assumes that all these

operations synchronously update the bounds of NativeWidgetMac. This

change at least makes the eventual state more correct.



In this particular bug, window positioning got messed up because

many SetSize calls were made before the initial bounds of the window

were determined/cached in the browser process.

entry.title: [Downloads] Format and simplify/truncate URLs on chrome://downloads page
entry.content:
This tweaks the behavior of chrome://downloads items' displayed URLs

in several ways:



1. Sends a formatted display version of the URL from the browser, in

particular with IDNs properly displayed in Unicode and extraneous

portions of the URL omitted, which previously could be used to

mislead the user, e.g. by making the actual hostname not visible

(using a very long user/password).

3. Refuses to link displayed URLs if they were truncated due to the mojo

message size limit (c.f. crbug.com/1070451). Such truncated URLs

won't work properly anyway, so there is no point in linking them.



Screencasts and demo page:

https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1b_HO0Knzm7yJAFLTVbKFCR2ARCZ916LM



Observe in screencasts:

1st link - Before: User can be misled by fake domain name in username.

After: The user/pass components are omitted.

2nd link - Before: The long data URL is clickable in chrome://downloads

despite having been truncated for being > 2 MB.

After: The long data URL is not clickable.

3rd link - Before: IDN is displayed in unreadable punycode.

After: IDN is displayed in readable characters.

entry.title: Refactor how wpt handles fuzzy color matching
entry.content:
Both computed and valid color tests previous looked for exact matching

of strings. This became untenable with color-mix and relative color

syntax because of potential float rounding errors. e.g.:



color-mix(in lch, color(srgb 1 0 0) 100%, black)

Will simply return red in the lch color space.

chromium: lch(54.29 106.854 40.856)

firefox: lch(54.2905 106.846 40.855)

safari: lch(54.288002 106.83335 40.852623)



These numbers are all obviously extremely similar. If we want more

alignment on how floats are serialized, it should be tested elsewhere.



This CL adds a custom comparsionFunction to css valid and computed

tests. For colors this test will strip out numbers and compare them

with an epislon, then compare other parts of the string directly to

validate formatting and color space. The algorithm itself is moved

from computed-testcommon.js

entry.title: [RenderDocument] Flush synthetic events before web test start
entry.content:
Enabling RenderDocument causes same-origin navigations to swap to a new

RenderFrameHost. However, when a RenderFrameHost is changed, the browser

dispatches synthetic mouse events to ensure the renderer knows where the

mouse cursor is. In web tests using the event_sender API, events are

injected into Blink synchronously so the browser-generated synthetic

events may be processed after test events which can affect test output.



This CL changes the web test runner to ensure all synthetic events have

been flushed and processed before the test is started. It does this by

blocking parsing in a web test until input has been flushed, the order

of events from the perspective of WebTestControlHost:



* Initial-state/Test Finished: Set a `next_nav_is_new_test` bit.

* READY_TO_COMMIT: If `next_nav_is_new_test` - call

BlockTestUntilStart in the renderer which blocks parsing in the

current DocumentLoader, before it starts loading the new document.

* : Post a task to generate the synthetic

events.

* DID_FINISH_NAVIGATION: If `next_nav_is_new_test` - clear the bit and

post a task to:

* Flush input - this waits until all input has been IPC'd to the

renderer and ACK'd. Note: input may still be queued in

renderer-side compositor or main thread queues.

* Calls StartTest on the renderer.

* StartTest (in renderer)

* Flushes the compositor queue to ensure all its input has been

processed (this may result in queueing input on the main thread).

* Flushes the main thread event queue.

* Unblocks the parser.

entry.title: Adjust Desktop privacy guide for hash-prefix real-time lookups
entry.content:
Changes:

- When the friendlier settings feature is enabled, modifies the

sublabel of Safe Browsing standard protection.

- When the friendlier settings features is disabled, modifies the

some additional details in the Safe Browsing standard protection

description (FeatureDescription2 + PrivacyDescription1).



Note that the "off" branch for hash-prefix real-time lookups will be

long-lived, so this does not follow the general strategy of adding the

disabled case only in the "FlagsDisabled" suite.



Test changes:

- `label` is added to PrivacyGuideDescriptionItemElement so that tests

can read it.

- New child test suites added to the SafeBrowsingFragment suite:

1) HashPrefixRealTimeDisabled

2) HashPrefixRealTimeEnabled

3) HashPrefixRealTimeEnabled_FriendlierSettingsDisabled

- The test suite SafeBrowsingFragment_FlagsDisabled is renamed to

FlagsDisabled since it is already a child suite of the suite

SafeBrowsingFragment.

- The test UpdatedStandardProtectionPrivacyGuide is renamed to

StandardProtectionDescription and is moved within the child suite

HashPrefixRealTimeDisabled.

- The HashPrefixRealTimeDisabled and HashPrefixRealTimeEnabled suites

are expected to stick around long-term, whereas the FlagsDisabled and

HashPrefixRealTimeEnabled_FriendlierSettingsDisabled suites contain

only temporary test cases.

entry.title: [autofill in devtools] Emit filled fields information to devtools.
entry.content:
This CL uses the newly added Observer. We react to a form being filled and in the case where its an address form, the filled_fields info

is sent to devtools.



Regarding the profile and the address used to fill the form:

1. Unfortunately CDP does not allow to have an array of arrays

therefore the current API has to nest objects, see AddressUI.

2. We are using AutofillAddressUIComponent to build the address UI

representation. This is a 2D array, where each inner array will

have a an object of type `AddressField`, this is what devtool will get:



[

[{name: "GIVE_NAME", value: "Bruno"},

{name: "FAMILY_NAME", value: "Braga"}],

[{name: "CITY", value: "Munich"},

{name: "ZIP", value: "81456"}],

]



which it can use to build:



Bruno Braga

Munich 81456



3. Sending address information to devtools is safe because developers do not have access to it AND autofill is under an experimental domain.

entry.title: Avoid crashing when loading the same profile twice
entry.content:
This CL adds debug information in crash keys to help identify the cause

for the double-loading of profiles.



This specifically target the case where one (or more) asynchronous loads

are in flight when a synchronous load is attempted. It should not change

existing behavior, except in scenarios that were crashing.



It logs the call stack of the most recent asynchronous load, as well as

the profile path (if the profile path is different, then the call stack

is not useful and should be ignored).



The crash is converted to DumpWithoutCrashing(), and Chrome now

waits until the asynchronous load finishes, by actively spinning the

run loop. This is only a workaround.



Cleaner fixes could be:

- remove the synchronous load from the startup code, and use only the

asynchronous API. This is not easy to do, because the profile is

currently loaded very early in the startup, at a time where the message

loop is not started yet.

- Change the asynchronous callers to wait until a later point in the

startup sequence, to avoid conflicting with the initial synchronous

load. Hopefully this CL will allow identifying these callers.
